PART 2 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
Purpose and Effect This Part of the Statement of Operating Conditions contains the general terms and conditions under which Columbia Gas of Pennsylvania, Inc. (“the Company”) will provide NGPA Section 311 Gas Transportation Service in interstate commerce to qualifying shippers, including both end-users and suppliers of natural gas or renewable natural gas, under Rate LDS-Large Distribution Service and Rate SDS-Small Distribution Service, pursuant to the Company’s Blanket Certificate of Limited Jurisdiction issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Section 1 – General Provisions and Definitions
1.1 Filing and Posting
This Statement of Operating Conditions is on file with FERC and may be accessed under the eTariff section of its website at www.ferc.gov.
1.2 Revisions
This Statement of Operating Conditions may be revised, amended, supplemented, or otherwise modified from time to time subject to the approval of the Commission.
1.3 Application of Statement
The provisions of the Statement of Operating Conditions shall apply to any party or parties lawfully receiving gas transportation service from the Company under the rates set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently Effective Rates, and the receipt of gas transportation service shall constitute the receiver a Shipper of the Company as the term is used herein.
1.4 Rules and Regulations
The rules, regulations, and other terms contained in this Statement of Operating Conditions are part of every contract or agreement for service, whether written, oral or implied, made by the Company for service hereunder.
1.5 Statement of Agents
No agent or employee of the Company has authority to make any promise, agreement, or representation inconsistent with the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
1.6 Definitions
The following definitions shall apply to this Statement of Operating Conditions, unless otherwise clearly indicated:
(1) “Applicant” means any person, firm, corporation, or other entity that (i) desires to take gas transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions at one or more specific locations, (ii) complies completely with all Company requirements for obtaining natural gas transportation service hereunder, (iii) has requested and is awaiting Company approval of its request for service, and (iv) is not yet actually receiving such service from the Company. An Applicant shall become a Shipper for purposes of this Statement of Operating Conditions only after it actually starts receiving the applicable service(s) from the Company.
(2) “Authorized Transportation Volume” means the maximum amount of gas that a Shipper may transport during a period of interruption or limitation imposed under Section 19.7 of this Part.
(3) “BCF” means one billion (1,000,000,000) cubic feet of gas. This is a measure of gas usage.
(4) “Billing Cycle” means the regularly recurring period from one meter reading or estimated meter reading to the subsequent meter reading or estimated meter reading, upon which a Shipper’s bill for service is rendered. A billing cycle need not coincide with a calendar month.
(5) “BTU” or “British thermal unit” is the amount of heat energy needed to raise the temperature of one pound of water by one degree F.
(6) “CCF” is a measure of gas usage and means one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas.
(7) “City Gate” means the point where interstate pipelines deliver gas into the Company’s facilities or receive gas from the Company’s facilities.
(8) “Commercial Customer” means a Shipper using gas in an establishment of a commercial or service nature, including, without limitation, wholesale and retail stores, warehouses, office buildings, restaurants, garages, and government agencies. (9) “Commission” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
(10) “Company” means Columbia Gas of Pennsylvania, Inc., a Pennsylvania corporation that provides natural gas distribution service subject to the jurisdiction of the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission and NGPA Section 311 gas transportation service pursuant to a Limited Jurisdiction Certificate granted by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
(11) “Delivery Point” or “Point of Delivery” means the point at which the Company delivers gas to or on behalf of a Shipper.
(12) “Distribution”, “Distribution Service” and “Natural Gas Distribution Service” mean NGPA Section 311 Gas Transportation Service provided by the Company under this Statement of Operating Conditions, unless the context otherwise requires.
(13) “Distribution Charge” means the basic service charges for the delivery of natural gas from the Receipt Point to one or more designated Delivery Points.
(14) “Distribution Pipeline” means any Company pipeline other than a Transmission Pipeline or Company service line.
(15) “Dth” or “Dekatherm” means ten (10) therms.
(16) “EBB” means an Electronic Bulletin Board system.
(17) “Electronic Flow Corrector” or “EFC” means a device that may be attached to a meter with an instrumentation drive and is used to correct measured usage to standard conditions based on actual pressure and temperature.
(18) “End-User” means an Industrial Customer or Commercial Customer using gas in its own business or operations.
(19) “FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
(20) “FTS” means firm transportation service provided by an interstate pipeline in which gas is transported on a firm basis from designated receipt points to designated delivery points.
(21) “Gas” or “Natural Gas” or “Natural Gas Supply” shall mean the hydrocarbon gas obtained from underground and undersea porous sedimentary rocks or renewable natural gas, as defined herein.
(22) “Human Needs” or “Essential Human Needs” or “Essential Human Needs Use” shall mean gas usage by customers for service to any buildings where persons normally dwell, including but not limited to, residences, apartment houses, dormitories, hotels, motels, hospitals, correctional institutions, and nursing homes, as well as the use of natural gas by sewage plants.
(23) “Industrial Customer” means a Shipper using gas for creating or changing raw or unfinished material into another form or product through the application of heat or heat treating, steam agitation, evaporation, baking, drying, distilling, or other processes. This term includes, without limitation, manufacturing plants, machine shops, steel and iron mills, lumber mills, food processing facilities, and petrochemical operations in which gas is the raw material.
(24) "Instrumentation Drive” means a mechanism that may be attached to some types of meters that provides the ability to install a flow correcting device to the meter.
(25) “ITS” means interruptible transportation service provided by an interstate pipeline, in which natural gas is transported on an interruptible basis.
(26) “Local Market Area” shall mean a continuous physically interconnected system of Company-owned distribution piping through which the Company provides natural gas service to customers in a discrete geographic area, utilizing one or more common points of receipt from an interstate pipeline supplier(s) or local gas supplier(s).
(27) “Maximum Daily Quantity” or “MDQ” means a Shipper’s maximum usage during a 24-hour period based on recent historical Shipper transportation data.
The Company shall perform an MDQ calculation each year based on data ending March 31 and shall provide the new MDQ to Shippers and/or their agents of record in September. The newly calculated MDQ will be effective beginning with the November billing cycle. An adjustment to the MDQ may be made at any time upon agreement between the Shipper and the Company. The MDQ will be calculated as follows unless otherwise specified in this Statement of Operating Conditions:
a. For Monthly Read Meters, a regression analysis comparing monthly degree days to monthly transportation volumes based on a minimum of twelve (12) months and a maximum of thirty-six (36) months will be developed to calculate the MDQ.
i. When the regression analysis yields an R Squared value greater than 0.6, the MDQ will be based on the regression analysis and the following calculation will be used to determine the MDQ:
MDQ = Base Load + Heat Load * (Market Area Design Day Degree Days)
ii. When the regression analysis yields an R Squared value less than 0.6, the MDQ will be based on the highest monthly transportation volume in the prior three years and the following calculation will be used to determine the MDQ:
MDQ = Highest Monthly Transportation Volume in Past Three Years / 25 days
b. For daily read meters, the MDQ will be based on the highest daily transportation volume in the past three years.
c. For new meters or new Shipper usage without sufficient monthly or daily data, the MDQ will be based on currently-available information until the next MDQ update.
(28) “Mcf” means one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas.
(29) “Month” means calendar month.
(30) “NGPA” means the Natural Gas Policy Act, 15 U.S.C. §§ 3301-3432.
(31) “Nomination EBB” means the electronic bulletin board and nomination system, which is used for scheduling gas transportation on the Company’s system.
(32) “PAPUC” means the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission.
(33) “Pipeline Scheduling Point” or “PSP” means a point or points of interconnection with an upstream interstate pipeline at which a Shipper will schedule deliveries to the Company, or to which the Company will transport gas on behalf of a Shipper. Such point or points shall consist of the following: interconnections with Eastern Gas Transmission and Storage, Inc.; Equitrans, L.P.; National Fuel Gas Supply Corporation; Tennessee Gas Pipeline Company; Texas Eastern Transmission, LP; and Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC. The interconnections with Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC include the Market Areas and Master List of Interconnections as defined in the General Terms and Conditions of the FERC Gas Tariff of Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC. As of May 1, 2010, those scheduling points included 25E-25 (Lancaster), 25-26 (Bedford), 25E-29 (Downington), 25-35 (Pittsburgh); 25-36 (Olean); 25-38 (Rimersburg); 25-39 (New Castle); and 25-40 (PA/WV Misc).
(34) “Primary FTS” with regard to Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC capacity shall mean Firm Transportation Service which has a designated primary delivery point located in the same Pipeline Scheduling Point in which the Shipper is located and has a designated primary receipt point at a location considered to be a point of generally available supply. “Primary FTS” with regard to any other interstate pipeline shall mean firm transportation service which has a designated primary delivery point located in the same Company Local Market Area in which the Shipper is located and has a designated primary receipt point at a location considered to be a point of generally available supply
(35) “Receipt Point” or “Point of Receipt” means the point at which a Shipper delivers gas to the Company for subsequent transportation under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
(36) “Renewable Natural Gas” means gas, consistently primarily of methane, which (1) is derived from biogas produced by landfills, animal farms, wastewater treatment plans, or other sources, and (2) is subsequently processed by removing carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and other constituents in order to convert the biogas into pipeline-compatible gaseous fuel.
(37) “Retainage” means gas lost and unaccounted for as more specifically defined in Part 1 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
(38) “Shipper” means an End-User or Supplier taking gas transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
(39) “Storage” means placing natural gas into an underground facility for removal and use at a later time.
(40) “Supplier” means an entity producing or furnishing natural gas or renewable natural gas for the use of others.
(41) “Telemetry” means an electronic communications process where the gas meter, equipped with an Electronic Flow Corrector and cellular modem or other telecommunications device utilized by the Company, electronically sends metering information to a host database of the Company. Shippers using meters with Telemetry will have the option of electing OFOs or OMOs for those meters as described in Part 3 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
(42) “Therm” or “thm” means a unit of heat equivalent to 100,000 British thermal units. The Company uses thm as the unit of measure for billing its Shippers. "Therm multiplier" shall mean a numeric multiplier that is applied to the volume of gas transported (as measured in cubic feet, CCF, or thousand cubic feet, MCF) to determine the amount of energy transported (as measured in therms). (43) “Transmission” means moving natural gas through the interstate pipeline system.
(44) “Transmission Pipeline” means pipelines and related facilities which are either: 1) owned by the Company in the form of a D-Line or a Company-owned pipeline that operates at a hoop stress of 20 percent or more of the specified minimum yield strength of the pipe as determined by 49 C.F.R § 192.3; or 2) pipelines and related facilities owned by another company which obtains at least 90% of its gas operating revenues from the transportation of gas for others and classifies at least 90% of its mains (other than service pipe) as field and gathering lines, storage, or transmission lines. The Company’s Shippers are not typically served directly from a Transmission Pipeline, and the Company reserves the right to remove, relocate, or abandon its Transmission Pipelines, subject to any required regulatory approvals.
Section 2 – Service Limitations 2.1 Availability
The Company’s service shall not be used for any purpose other than those covered by the availability provisions of the rate schedule under which service is provided.
2.2 Transmission Lines
Transmission Pipelines or high pressure “D-Line” distribution facilities, from which gas may be delivered to customers along the route thereof, are not intended and cannot be maintained solely for service to such customers. The Company may refuse to render gas transportation service on or from such pipelines in those instances where hazardous conditions of service might result from the pressures involved; where the service is subject to early termination or partial or complete failure arising from depletion or insufficiency of local gas supply; where the costs incident to rendering service would be of such nature as to result in undue or unreasonable discrimination against other customers; or where for other reasons, such as the temporary nature of certain pipelines, the service would be of short duration, hazardous, or inadequate. Section 3 – Application Process 3.1 Application All Applicants desiring transportation service from the Company under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall submit a written application for such service in the form prescribed by the Company. The Application and Agreement shall set forth: (1) the Receipt Point(s) at which the gas will be delivered to the Company; (2) the Delivery Point(s) at which the Company will deliver the Shipper’s gas; and (3) the Shipper’s proposed Maximum Daily Quantity and annual quantity. The Application and Agreement shall also include: the name, address, and telephone number to which all notices are to be delivered, an e-mail address, banking and balancing information if applicable, and the services and levels of those services to be rendered. In addition, the Applicant shall provide the Company with the names of two persons, along with their 24/7 contact numbers and e-mail addresses (if available), who are to be contacted in the event that interruption of gas service is required under Section 19.7 of this Part.
An Applicant seeking service under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall indicate whether it seeks service under Rate LDS or Rate SDS, and shall submit information demonstrating that it qualifies for service under that rate schedule. The Company will, at the request of the Applicant, assist in determining whether the Applicant qualifies for such service.
In the Application and Agreement, the Shipper has the option of appointing an agent to act on its behalf and obtain from the Company any and all pertinent information necessary to establish and administer the Company’s gas transportation service for the Shipper. The Shipper has the right to change the appointment of an agent to act on its behalf by submitting a new Application and Agreement containing the new appointment.
3.2 Evaluation of Application
Within sixty (60) days of receipt of all necessary information requested by the Company to evaluate an application, the Company will respond to the Applicant and either agree to supply service or deny service. The Company may place limitations on the amount or character of service it will supply, or may reject applications for any of the following reasons: (a) The Applicant has not complied with federal, state, or municipal laws and regulations governing gas service.
(b) The Company lacks adequate facilities to render the service requested. (c) The service requested is likely to adversely affect service to other customers of the Company. (d) The applicant's installation of piping or gas equipment is, in the judgment of the Company, hazardous or of such a character that satisfactory service cannot be rendered.
(e) An extension or construction of new facilities is required to furnish such service.
(f) The requested service is from a Transmission Pipeline as specified in Section 2.2 -Transmission Lines.
(g) The Applicant did not satisfactorily establish creditworthiness.
If the Company refuses to provide the requested service, the Company shall provide detailed support for its decision.
3.3 Acceptance
Acceptance of service by the Shipper shall constitute an agreement to accept service under this Statement of Operating Conditions, the orders and regulations of the Commission, the laws of the United States, and the laws of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
3.4 Adjustment of Maximum Daily Quantity and Annual Quantity
The Maximum Daily Quantity and annual quantity are subject to adjustment by the Company no more than one time each year, to reflect the Shipper’s currently-effective Maximum Daily Quantity based on data ending March 31 and annual adjustment quantities experienced in the most recent November to October period, except that an adjustment may be made at any time upon agreement of the Shipper and the Company.
Section 4 – Shipper’s Installations and Company Equipment
4.1 Point of Connection
The Company will designate the point at which the Company’s facilities will interconnect with those of the Shipper. The furnishing of such information does not constitute an agreement or obligation on the part of the Company to render service.
4.2 Meter(s) and Other Company Facilities
The Company shall have the right to determine the location of its meters, regulators, calorimeters, monitoring equipment, and other facilities necessary to provide service under this Statement of Operating Conditions. The Shipper shall provide, free of expense to the Company, a space satisfactory to the Company for all such facilities. The Company reserves the right to establish standards as to the location, size, fire-proofing, ventilation, and other attributes of such space in accordance with pressure conditions, quantities, and other pertinent factors. In certain buildings, the Company may require that an approved meter room be provided.
4.4 Interference with Facilities
Without prior written notice to the Company, the Shipper shall not open, tamper or interfere with, in any manner, its service line or with any regulator or regulators or safety appliances installed in connection with service to the Shipper, irrespective of ownership thereof, except to see that same are kept in proper working order. Neither shall the Shipper increase or decrease the pressure of same without the written approval of the Company. Any Shipper action taken that may endanger the safety of a person or the integrity of the Company’s delivery system will be grounds for immediate termination without notice as specified in Section 16, Termination of Service, of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
4.5 Shipper’s Responsibility
Shipper assumes all responsibility for the ownership, maintenance, and repair of all piping, facilities, or other property on Shipper’s side of the point of connection. All such piping and other facilities or property must meet the Company’s standards and specifications. Shipper will save Company harmless from and against all claims for injury or damage to persons or property occasioned by or in any way resulting from such piping, facilities, or other property on Shipper’s side of the point of connection.
Section 5 – Testing and Inspecting Shipper’s Installations
The Company shall have the right, but not the obligation, to inspect any Shipper-owned piping or other facilities at all times, and may reject any such facilities that do not meet the Company’s standards or specifications. However, the Company does not assume responsibility for any defective materials or faulty workmanship with respect to Shipper-owned facilities, and any such inspection by the Company, or failure to inspect or reject, shall not render the Company liable or responsible for any loss or damage resulting from defects in such facilities.
The first inspection at any premises shall be without charge, but additional inspections requested by the Shipper or required because of unsatisfactory conditions disclosed by the first inspection shall be subject to a charge set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates.
Section 6 – Creditworthiness
The Company shall perform a creditworthiness evaluation of the Applicant or Shipper, including an assessment of the credit risk exposure resulting from the rates for services contained in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. The Company shall not be required to initiate or maintain service to any Shipper who is or has become insolvent or who, at the Company’s request, fails within a commercially reasonable time to demonstrate creditworthiness, as determined by the Company in its reasonable discretion.
Section 7– Delivery Point
In the case of an End-User, the Delivery Point shall be the outlet side of the Company’s meter. In the case of a supplier of natural gas or renewable natural gas, the Delivery Point shall be the point of interconnection with an interstate pipeline or other designated point selected by the Shipper for delivery of such natural gas or renewable natural gas.
Section 8 – Extensions and Construction of New Facilities
Service under this Statement of Operating Conditions will normally be provided from the Company’s existing gas distribution system and the Company shall have no obligation to extend its distribution system or construct new facilities to provide such service. If an Applicant requests service hereunder that would require a main extension or other new facilities and the Company is willing and able construct those facilities, it shall first conduct an economic analysis that considers, among other factors, the capital investment required to construct such facilities and the net present value of the anticipated revenues from the Applicant. To the extent that such analysis shows that all or a portion of the required capital investment is not economically justified at the Company’s expense, the Applicant will be required to pay the Company a non-refundable contribution-in-aid- of-construction equal to that portion of the required investment that is not economically justified, or enter into another mutually acceptable arrangement with the Company that ensures that the Company’s remaining customers are not required to subsidize service to the Applicant. Applicant shall also be required to pay the cost of any additional equipment required to provide the requested service, including any equipment necessary to monitor the gas quality of natural gas or renewable natural gas delivered by the Shipper to the Company for transportation under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
Section 9 – Rights-of-Way
9.1 Company Facilities on Applicant’s or Shipper’s Property
When, in order to serve an Applicant or Shipper, it is necessary to extend the Company's facilities over or through the Applicant or Shipper’s property, the Applicant or Shipper may be required to enter into a right-of-way agreement with the Company in which the Applicant or Shipper shall grant to the Company all necessary easements or rights-of-way on property owned by the Applicant or Shipper at no cost to the Company. Any such easement or right of way shall be recorded and shall run with the land. Applicant or Shipper will be required to save the Company harmless from claims to the easements or rights-of-way granted to the Company pursuant to this Section.
9.2 Procurement by Applicant or Shipper
When, in order to provide gas transportation service to an Applicant or Shipper, it is necessary to extend the Company’s facilities over or through the property of a third party, the Applicant or Shipper shall, at a minimum, use its best efforts to assist the Company in acquiring any necessary easements or rights-of-way on property owned by third parties. The Applicant or Shipper may be required to secure to, and for, the Company, all necessary and convenient easements or rights-of- way and to pay the costs incident thereto. The Applicant or Shipper shall accept service subject to any limitations or restrictions contained in the easement or right-of-way agreement.
9.3 Delays
Applications for service from facilities to be constructed where a right-of-way is not owned by the Company will only be accepted subject to delays incident to obtaining a satisfactory easement or right-of-way. The Company shall not be obligated to proceed with capital expenditures and any agreement by the Company to construct facilities to serve the Applicant or Shipper may be terminated at the discretion of the Company if: (1) the Applicant or Shipper fails to enter into a right-of-way agreement or easement with the Company as required by the provisions of this Section regarding Company Facilities on Applicant or Shipper’s Property; or (2) the Company is not able to obtain such third party easements or rights-of-way upon terms and conditions (including cost) mutually agreeable to the Company and such third party property owner(s). In the event of such termination, the Applicant or the Shipper shall be responsible for all costs expended or obligated by the Company related to the proposed facilities at the time of termination.
Section 10 – Company Facilities on Shipper’s Premises
10.1 Shipper’s Responsibility
The Shipper shall be responsible for safe keeping of the Company's property while located on the Shipper’s premises. In the event of injury or destruction of any such property from the act of negligence of the Shipper or Shipper’s agent, the Shipper shall pay the costs of repairs and replacement.
10.2 Protection by Shipper
The Shipper shall protect the equipment of the Company on Shipper’s premises, and shall not permit any person, except a Company employee having proper Company identification, to break any seals upon, or do any work on, any meter, service pipe, monitoring equipment, or other facilities of the Company located on the Shipper’s premises.
10.3 Tampering
In the event of the Company's meters or other property being tampered or interfered with, the Shipper being served through such equipment shall pay the amount which may be reasonably estimated to be due for service used but not registered on the Company's meter, and for any repairs, replacements or changes in facilities required, as well as for costs of inspections, investigations, and protective installations.
10.4 Access to Premises
The Company or its authorized agents shall have access at all reasonable times to the property or premises to which gas is transported, or from which natural gas or renewable natural gas is received, to determine if the gas is being carried, transported, and burned in a proper and safe manner and in accordance with this Statement of Operating Conditions, or to read, inspect, and test the meter or house lines and other appliances, equipment, or facilities. Refusal on the part of the Shipper to allow access to Shipper’s premises shall constitute sufficient cause for terminating service to such premises.
In the event the Shipper does not provide access during a 12 consecutive billing cycle period to read the meter, upon notice from the Company, the Shipper must choose from one of the following three options:
(1) To schedule a service call to gain access to the premises for purposes of inspection or meter reading. The Company will provide one service call annually to Shippers for the purpose of gaining access. If a Shipper requests to schedule an additional service call during a 12 consecutive billing cycle period, the Shipper will be assessed a charge for a one-hour service call. Additionally, if the Shipper fails to meet a scheduled appointment without good cause and without providing a 24-hour notice of cancellation, the Company may charge for one hour of service time. If the Company fails to meet a scheduled appointment without good cause and without providing 24-hour notice of cancellation, the Company may credit the Customer's account with a credit equal to one hour of service time; or
(2) To install, at the Shipper’s expense, telemetering facilities for purposes of monitoring and/or billing Shipper transportation volumes. Shipper shall provide and maintain phone and/or electric lines to the location of such facilities as specified by the Company; or
(3) To install an electronic meter-reading device for the purpose of monitoring and/or billing Shipper transportation volumes.
If the Shipper does not select one of the above three options within 60 days after notice from the Company, the Company reserves the right in its discretion to implement one of the above three options. If the Shipper refuses to allow the Company to implement one of the above three options, such refusal will be grounds for termination of service.
Section 11 – Service Continuity and Force Majeure
11.1 Regularity of Supply
The Company will use reasonable diligence to provide gas transportation service that is reasonably continuous, regular, and without interruption to those Shippers purchasing gas transportation service from the Company. The liability of the Company for damages for failure to transport Customer’s gas shall be limited to an amount equivalent to the Customer’s proportional monthly Customer Charge for the period of service during which a transportation failure occurs. In no event shall the Company be liable for extraordinary or consequential damages arising in any manner whatsoever as a result of a transportation failure.
11.2 Force Majeure
Neither Company nor Shipper shall be liable in damages to the other for any act, omission, or circumstance occasioned by or in consequence of any events of force majeure, including acts of God; accidents or other casualties; strikes, lockouts, or other labor disputes affecting the Company or its suppliers of gas; acts of the public enemy; war; blockades; insurrections; riots; epidemics; landslides, lighting, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, or other natural catastrophes; arrests and restraints of rulers and peoples; civil disturbances; explosions; breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe, the binding order of any court or governmental authority which has been resisted in good faith by all reasonable legal means; changes in circumstances, law, or governmental regulation or order (including, without limitation, any such law, regulation or order, including an order of the Commission, which alters, affects, limits, or interrupts, directly or indirectly, Shipper’s right to transport gas hereunder); and any other cause, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably with in the control of the party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Failure to prevent or settle any strike or strikes shall not be considered to be a matter within the control of the party claiming suspension.
Other than the Responsible Party’s obligation to make payments of amounts due hereunder and the Shipper’s duty to provide adequate supplies of gas, in the event that either party hereto is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by force majeure, to carry out its obligations under this Statement of Operating Conditions, it is agreed that upon notice of such force majeure in writing or by telephone to the other party as soon as reasonably possible after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the obligations of the party giving such notice, insofar as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuation of any inability so caused, but for no longer period, and such cause shall be remedied by such party with all reasonable dispatch. Telephone notices given under the provisions of this Section shall be confirmed in writing as soon as reasonably possible, and all notices hereunder shall specifically state the time and date when the force majeure became effective. The obligations under this Statement of Operating Conditions shall not be terminated by reason of any such force majeure, but shall remain in full force and effect for the entire term specified herein.
Section 12 –Shipper’s Use of Service
12.1 Precautions to be Taken by Shipper
The responsibility for detection of defects and leaks on the Shipper’s premises and in the service line or other facilities owned by the Shipper is upon the Shipper. “Defects” shall mean, among other things, failure or deficiency of gas, irregular supply, leakage, and excessive pressure. In case of detection of any defect within its premises, the Shipper shall causes the premises to be vacated immediately and notify the Company so that the conditions existing may receive prompt and proper attention. When gas has been shut off because of a leak in Shipper-owned piping or facilities or other hazardous conditions of service, service shall not be restored until such leak or other hazardous conditions have been repaired and made safe either by a competent plumber or gas-fitter.
12.2 Liability for Damages
In the absence of proof of causal negligence, the Company shall not be liable for any injury to persons or damage to property arising or accruing in any manner whatsoever from the supplying or use of gas.
Section 13 – Measurement
13.1 Measurement of Gas
Except as herein otherwise provided, the measurement of gas service shall be by meters purchased and installed by the Company. The meter will be of such size and type as the Company may determine to adequately serve the Shipper’s gas transportation requirements, and the Company may from time to time, change or alter the equipment to provide for accurate measurement. To determine measured transportation volumes, factors such as those for pressure, temperature, specific gravity, and deviation from the laws for ideal gases shall be applied.
13.2 Meters Not Available
In cases where meters are not available due to circumstances beyond the control of the Company, and the necessity for rendering gas transportation service to the Shipper is urgent, the Company may, by written agreement with the Shipper, commence service and render bills temporarily on the basis of estimated gas consumption, determined in accordance with Section 13.5, Estimated Usage, of this Part.
13.3 Measuring Equipment
Unless otherwise agreed upon, the Company will own, install, maintain, and operate measuring stations equipped with displacement or flow meters and other necessary measuring equipment to determine the quantity of gas transported. The gas transported shall be measured in accordance with the latest approved methods in use in the industry generally. Orifice meters shall be installed and operated, and gas quantities computed, in accordance with Report No. 3 of the Gas Measurement Committee of the American Gas Association, as amended, expanded, or superseded from time to time, applied in a practical and appropriate manner. Displacement meter readings shall be adjusted for pressure and temperature conditions. Shipper may install check measuring equipment, provided such equipment is installed so as not to interfere with the operations of the Company and its equipment. The Company and Shipper, in the presence of each other, shall have access to the other’s measuring equipment at all reasonable times, but, unless otherwise agreed upon, the reading, calibrating, and adjustment thereof and the changing of charts shall be done only by the owner thereof. Both parties shall have the right to be present at the time of any installing, reading, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting done in connection with the other’s measuring equipment. The records from such measuring equipment shall remain the property of the owner, but, upon request, each will submit to the other its records and charts, together with calculations therefrom, for inspection, subject to return within thirty (30) days after receipt thereof. Shipper shall exercise reasonable care in the installation, maintenance, and operation of its equipment so as to avoid any inaccuracy in the determination of the quantity of gas delivered.
Equipment necessary to provide Telemetry shall be an option available to Shipper accounts that are served under this Statement of Operating Conditions when the existing meter at the Shipper’s facility is equipped with an instrumentation drive. The meter and associated Telemetry equipment shall be the property of the Company and the Company will be responsible for installing and maintaining the equipment.
When Shipper-owned analog telephone lines are used by the Company to obtain the daily meter reading information, the installation, maintenance, and repair of the analog telephone lines and the monthly costs associated with such analog telephone lines will be the sole responsibility of the Shipper.
13.4 Meter Reading
The Company may read any of its meters at least once each billing cycle. The meter reading is used to determine a Shipper’s transportation volumes for billing.
The Company may determine a meter reading for billing purposes by 1) sending a representative to the location of the meter at the Shipper’s premises to obtain the reading; 2) using Telemetry to upload the meter reading; 3) dialing a Shipper-provided analog telephone number established to provide the meter reading; 4) estimating a meter reading after unsuccessfully attempting to obtain an actual reading; or 5) obtaining a reading using an automated meter reading device.
(a) Estimated Meter Reading
The Company may estimate a meter reading if: 1) the Company’s agent or representative is unable to gain access to the meter; 2) the meter or the meter reading dial has malfunctioned thus preventing the meter from reflecting an accurate reading, or 3) other circumstances exist that prevent the Company from reading the meter.
When the Company is unable to obtain an actual meter reading, an estimated meter reading shall be used to determine the transportation volumes. The estimated reading will be based on prior transportation volumes for a similar period of time and corrected for current conditions.
In order to avoid a bill based on an estimated meter reading, a Shipper may record the meter reading and submit it to the Company. If such reading is received by the Company the bill for the current billing cycle may be calculated using the meter reading provided by the Shipper instead of the meter reading estimated by the Company.
(b) Automated Meter Reading
All readings by an Automated Meter Reading (AMR) device shall be deemed actual readings. Upon a Shipper’s request, the Company shall secure an in-person meter reading to confirm the accuracy of an automatic meter reading device when a Shipper disconnects service or a new service request is received. The Company may charge a fee to obtain the in-person meter reading.
(c) Daily Meter Reading using Analog Telephone Lines
A Shipper utilizing analog telephone service as the communication line that the Company uses to obtain daily measurement information on a daily basis, shall no longer hold the Company responsible for providing daily measurement information on a daily basis if and when the telecommunications company discontinues analog service to the Shipper.
(d) Daily Meter Reading by Telemetry
Electronic access to a meter’s daily measurement information using Telemetry shall be available to a Shipper or the Shipper’s specified agent of record when:
1. an instrumentation drive exists on the meter that serves the Shipper’s facility; and
2. all equipment necessary to capture, correct, and transmit the daily meter reading to the Company has been installed.
The transportation volumes for the gas day ending at 10:00 AM Eastern Time shall be available electronically through a secure internet address by 1:00 PM Eastern Time that same calendar day for the Shipper, the Shipper’s current agent of record, or any other Shipper-authorized party.
13.5 Estimated Usage
The Company may use an estimated meter reading to determine transportation volumes for billing. Volumes are estimated when: (1) any meter or measuring device fails to register the actual gas transportation volumes for any period of time; or (2) the Company is unable to obtain a meter reading for causes beyond its control.
In those instances where, during normal working hours, the Company's agent or representative is unable to gain access to the meter to obtain a meter reading, the number of estimated readings shall be limited to six consecutive months, and the Shipper’s service, thereafter, is subject to termination.
The estimated transportation volumes shall be determined by subtracting the previous meter reading, whether actual or estimated, from the current estimated meter reading. For billing purposes, the estimated volumes are subject to a therm adjustment, and where applicable, a temperature and pressure adjustment. The estimated volumes will be used to calculate the Shipper’s bill.
The Shipper shall be obligated to pay the bill based on the estimated transportation volumes as though the bill was based on an actual meter reading. The Shipper’s gas transportation service will be subject to termination for failure to pay the bill as specified in Section 18, Termination of Service.
Bills for volumes based on estimated meter readings shall be subject to adjustment for any unusual circumstances found to have affected the quantity of gas transported, or for obvious errors in estimates. When an actual meter reading is obtained that indicates previous estimates are inaccurate, adjustments to the estimates shall be reflected in the next bill issued to the Shipper.
13.6 Flowing Temperature
The Company shall determine the temperature of the natural gas flowing through the meter or meters by recorder, from established tables for the location involved, or by use of temperature- transmitting elements used in conjunction with electronic measuring devices.
13.7 Therm Adjustment
The Company shall apply a therm multiplier to metered cubic foot volumes to adjust for heating value. In the case of an End-User, this therm multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent reported heating value for the Pipeline Scheduling Point (“PSP”) within the Company’s service territory in which the Shipper’s meter is located. In the case of a Supplier, this therm multiplier shall be calculated monthly based on the most recent heating value measured at the Receipt Point.
Section 14 – Meter Tests 14.1 Meter Tests
The Company shall have the right to test any meter at any time at its expense and, if such test discloses the meter is registering on an average (a) more than two percent (2%) slow; (b) more than two percent (2%) fast, or if the meter is found not to register for any period, the Company shall render a bill or make a refund as the case may be.
14.2 Request Tests
The Shipper shall have the right to request the testing of its meter and the Company will, upon written application, have the same removed, sealed, and tested; subject, however, to the Shipper depositing with the Company the sum of money required to cover the expense of such test. If such meter, when tested, registers on an average between two percent (2%) fast and two percent (2%) slow, the meter shall be treated for all purposes hereof as registering correctly, and the said sum of money required to be deposited with the Company by the Shipper shall be forfeited to the Company to cover the cost of such test. If such test shall show such meter to be incorrect beyond the above allowable variations, then the Company shall return such deposit and make the necessary adjustment in billing. Section 15 – Payment Terms
15.1 Billing Period
Bills for service to all Shippers will be rendered monthly at the rates set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. 15.2 Payment Period
Bills are due upon transmittal and payment may be made by the Shipper by mailing a check to the address for payment designated on the bills, or at a Company-authorized collection agency, or any other method designated by the Company. The final date for payment will not fall on a Saturday, Sunday or holiday, and will be at least fifteen (15) days after transmittal. Failure to receive the bill will not excuse Shippers from payment obligations and payments must be made without regard to any counter claims whatsoever.
15.3 Payments by Mail
Any remittance received by mail at the address for payment designated by the Company on the Shipper’s bill, bearing U.S. Postal Service postmark date corresponding with or previous to the last date of payment, will be accepted by the Company as compliance with the terms of payment.
15.4 Disputed Bills
In the event of a dispute between the Shipper and the Company respecting any bill, the Company will forthwith make such investigation as may be required by the particular case and report the result thereof to the Shipper.
The first disputed bill investigation in a twelve consecutive billing cycle period will be provided at no charge, any subsequent request by the Shipper in the same twelve consecutive billing cycle period will be assessed the cost of the service call unless the investigation detects metering or some other Company error. The charge to the Shipper shall be limited to the Company’s costs based upon the actual time spent on the service call.
When the Company has made such a report to the Shipper, either (1) sustaining the bill as rendered or (2) submitting a corrected bill, the date of the bill for purposes of payment shall be considered to be as of the date of said report, and the Shipper shall pay the amount due within the time provided in this Statement of Operating Conditions, and failure to so pay shall render the Shipper liable for the penalties herein provided. Any amounts received by the Company in excess of the amount disclosed to be due by the Company’s investigation shall be forthwith returned to the Shipper if the error arose from any cause other than the incorrect estimating of a Shipper’s transportation volumes for the period in dispute. Errors arising through the incorrect estimating of a transportation volumes shall be adjusted in accordance with Section 13.5 of this Part.
15.5 Interest on Overpayments
The Company will pay interest on refunds of Shipper overpayments at the rate of six percent (6%) per annum without deduction for any taxes thereon, except where Shipper overpayments are refunded within ninety (90) days of overpayment.
15.6 Dishonored Tender of Payment
If the Company receives a check or other negotiable instrument from an Applicant or Shipper as payment of any bill, charge, or deposit due, and if such instrument is subsequently dishonored or is unable to be collected for any reason, the Company shall charge the Applicant or Shipper a service charge in the full amount permitted by law for each dishonored negotiable instrument. The service charge may be added to the monthly bill, or may be separately billed to the Applicant or Shipper.
Section 16 –Termination of Service
16.1 Definition Termination of service, as it applies to this Section 16, shall mean the cessation of service, whether temporary or permanent, without the consent of the Shipper.
16.2 Grounds for Termination of Service After notice as provided herein, the Company may terminate service provided to a Shipper for any of the following actions by the Shipper:
(a) Nonpayment of an undisputed delinquent account.
(b) Failure to comply with the material terms of a payment arrangement.
(c) Failure to establish or maintain creditworthiness.
(d) Failure to permit access to meters, service connections, or other property of the Company, including obstructed or hazardous access, for the purpose of replacement, maintenance, repair, or reading the meter or monitoring equipment.
(e) After having received notice of termination, a Shipper tenders payment to avoid termination or to obtain reconnection, and that payment is subsequently dishonored, revoked, or cancelled, and has not been remedied or full payment has not been rendered within three business days after notice by the Company as specified herein.
(f) Shipper has not delivered any gas to the Company for its account for a period of five consecutive days, and (1) the Shipper’s bank balance is insufficient to cover the transportation volumes or the Shipper did not have access to its bank balance due to the issuance of an Operational Flow Order (OFO) or Operational Matching Order (OMO), and (2) gas was delivered to or for Shipper on one or more days during such five-day period.
The Company may also remove its equipment in case of nonpayment of bill.
16.3 Notice of Termination of Service
Prior to terminating service, the Company shall provide written notice of the termination to the Shipper at least ten (10) days prior to the date of the proposed termination. The termination notice shall remain effective for 60 days. When a Shipper tenders a payment to avoid termination or to obtain reconnection of terminated service, and that same payment is subsequently dishonored, revoked, or cancelled, the Company shall issue a termination notice three days prior to a new date of service termination.
16.4 Grounds for Immediate Termination Without Prior Notice
Gas transportation service may be immediately terminated without prior notice in any of the following situations:
1. Fraud or material misrepresentation of the Shipper’s identity is used for the purpose of obtaining service.
2. Any Shipper action taken that may endanger the safety of a person or the integrity of the Company’s distribution system.
3. Tampering with meters or other Company equipment or unauthorized use.
4. Hazardous or defective Shipper installations.
5. Shipper’s equipment or use thereof might injuriously affect the equipment of the Company or the Company’s service to other customers.
Section 17 – Discontinuation of Service
Discontinuation of service means the cessation of service with the consent of the Shipper. A Shipper who intends to discontinue gas transportation service shall give at least seven (7) days' notice to the Company, which will then arrange for a final meter reading.
Section 18 – Quality of Gas Delivered to Company
18.1 Quality of Gas at Point(s) of Receipt with an Interstate Pipeline.
Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Points with an interstate pipeline shall conform to the interstate pipeline’s gas quality standards.
18.2 Quality of Gas at Other Point(s) of Receipt.
Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Points other than an interstate pipeline shall be commercially free from oil, water, air, salt, dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, harmful or noxious vapors, or other solid or liquid matter which might interfere with its merchantability or cause interference with proper operation of the lines, regulators, meters, and other equipment of Company or its customers. Shipper will indemnify and hold Company harmless from any suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses and expenses, including but not limited to, attorneys' fees and expenses, arising from personal injury, death, or damage to Company's equipment or facilities or arising from personal injuries, death, or damage to the facilities, products, or equipment of Company's other customers or third parties, or arising from additional hours worked by Company or its other customers or third parties, caused as a result of Shipper’s gas failing to meet the quality specifications set forth herein.

Such tests shall include only the test method or methods that tests for the specific standard or standards that were not met, but Company may consider any results provided by such test method(s). Company will provide Shipper with at least three (3) business days’ notice of the tests described in this Section 18.3, and Shipper will be given the opportunity to be present and observe such tests. Section 19 – Character of Gas Transportation Service
19.1 Deliveries by the Company The Company shall receive the quantities of gas supplied by the Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) and shall redeliver such quantities to Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Point(s), subject to the restrictions and limitations set forth in this Statement of Operating Conditions. All nominations must be performed through the Company's Nomination EBB. The quantity, pressure, and time of delivery shall be agreed to by the Company and the Shipper in advance, prior to delivery of gas supplies. It is the Shipper’s obligation to provide gas meeting the gas quality standards set forth in Section 18 of this Part to the Company at the agreed upon Receipt Points. 19.2 Title to Gas The Shipper warrants that it has good title to all natural gas or renewable natural gas delivered to the Company for transportation hereunder, and that such gas will be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances, and claims whatsoever, and that it will indemnify the Company, and save it harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of a breach of such warranty. 19.3 Retainage The Company shall retain a reasonable allowance of the total quantity of gas delivered into its system for the Shipper’s account, for gas which is lost or unaccounted for or used in the Company’s operations. The applicable retainage percentages are set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. 19.4 Order of Gas through the Meter. Gas through the Shipper’s meter during each billing cycle shall be considered to have come from the following sources, in order of priority: (a) Gas supplies which have reached the facilities of the Company on behalf of a Shipper. (b) The cumulative balance, if any, of excess deliveries in prior months. (c) Imbalance gas provided by the Company as defined in Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries.
19.5 Charges and Penalties of Other Pipelines or Distributors
If furnishing service, pursuant to the Shipper’s applicable gas transportation rate schedule, requires the Company to use a service provided other than by the Company, any cost incurred by, or billed to the Company, with regard thereto, shall be billed to the Shipper. The Shipper shall also reimburse the Company for penalties assessed to the Company under the applicable rate schedule of a third party pipeline or distributor as a result of daily excess transportation, daily excess tenders, excess monthly imbalances, banking imbalances, or other factors set forth in such rate schedules.
19.6 Retroactive Period Adjustments When the Company becomes aware of an overstatement or understatement of deliveries or nominations on a Shipper’s account for a previous period, the Company will adjust the Shipper’s account using the rates that were in effect for the billing cycle being adjusted.
19.7 Interruptions and Limitations of Gas Transportation Service The Company may interrupt or limit gas transportation service provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions in the following situations:
(a) When either the supply available to the Company or the Company’s system delivery capacity is not sufficient to simultaneously serve all non-firm customer requirements and maintain continuous, safe service to all firm customers;
(b) When interruption is necessary in order to perform maintenance or tests or make modifications, repairs, or replacements of the Company’s facilities or the facilities of its upstream suppliers;
(c) When the Company is unable to provide service due to events of force majeure, as defined in Section 11, Service Continuity and Force Majeure, of this Part;
(d) When Shipper has failed to deliver sufficient quantities of gas to the Company at the PSP behind which its Delivery Point is located or directly to the Company at a Receipt Point behind that PSP and the volumes available to the Shipper under Rider EBS-Elective Balancing Service are insufficient to make up the shortfall. Section 20 -- System Integrity Measures and Procedures.
20.1 In General
(a) Operational Alert (OA). An operational alert (OA) may be called during periods of projected increased or decreased consumer demand for, or supply of, gas which may cause system stress or threaten applicable storage or other pipeline contract limitations. An OA is a request for specific action on the part of one or more Shippers. The Shippers are expected to respond to OAs within four (4) hours after the Company has provided notice, informing the Company of their intended action(s). Where possible, an OA may be used to avoid an OFO or OMO, but shall not be required as a condition for the issuance of an OFO or OMO.
(b) Emergency Alerts (EAs). If an unforeseen emergency situation arises which could threaten the continuous adequate delivery of natural gas to a Shipper, the Company will provide the Shipper with as much notice as is reasonably possible under the emergency situation. Such notice shall be made by the medium most reasonably expected to reach the Shipper in a timely manner, including but not limited to, telephone, e-mail, facsimile, Nomination EBB, or personal contact. In such notice, the Company will advise the Shipper of the unforeseen emergency situation, and the Shipper is expected to comply with the Company’s requests.
(c) Seasonal Flow Orders (SFOs). As detailed below in the Seasonal Flow Order section of this Part, the Company shall have the authority to issue SFOs whenever the Company believes that the seasonal supplies of firm sales or transportation customers may be jeopardized. The Company may issue an SFO to Shippers in instances including, but not limited to, the following: (1) in order to prevent an excess of gas supply on the Company’s system, (2) to respond to an operational issue, or (2) to direct Shippers to adjust gas quantities being delivered to the Company to match Shippers’ estimated transportation requirements to prevent shortages of seasonal supplies on the Company’s system.
(d) Operational Flow Orders (OFOs) and Operational Matching Orders (OMOs). The Company has the authority to issue OFOs and OMOs whenever the Company believes that the daily safe and/or reliable operation of its distribution system may be jeopardized, including, without limitation, the need to protect the daily supply of firm sales and transportation customers. The Company will endeavor to take all actions reasonably practicable to avoid issuing an OFO or OMO. If the Company has the necessary information and conditions do not require a system-wide OFO or OMO, the Company may issue an OFO or OMO to an individual Shipper or group of Shippers, but this action shall not be a precondition for the Company to issue an OFO or OMO applicable to all Shippers. Where operationally feasible, the Company will endeavor to issue OFOs/OMOs by Pipeline Scheduling Point.
(1) Eligible Shippers may meet the requirements of SFOs, OFOs, and OMOs by subscribing to the Company’s Flow Order Management Service as described in Section 20.11 of this Part.
(2) If there is any change to the OFO or OMO status of a Shipper’s meter, the Company will, within thirty (30) days of the status change requested by the Shipper, notify the Shipper of such change.

20.4 Operational Flow Orders (OFOs)
(a) An OFO is a demand for specific actions on the part of Shippers. Shippers subject to OFOs are those Shippers:
(1) Who have meters without daily measurement equipment;
(2) With daily measurement equipped meters who have not elected Telemetry;
(3) Who have elected Telemetry and are awaiting installation of the new cellular modem device and whose existing meters are read daily using analog telephone lines when the analog line is not providing timely data;
(4) With meters whose transportation volumes are billed under Rate SDS.
(b) An OFO will be issued, to the extent possible, with a minimum of eight (8) hours’ notice to the affected parties. Notice shall be made by the medium most reasonably expected to reach the Shipper in a timely manner, including but not limited to e-mail, facsimile, or Nomination EBB. The notice will include the circumstance that warrants the issuance of the OFO or OMO, and it will explain why the actions are necessary.
(c) The Company will have the authority to direct Shippers to adjust daily transportation volumes to a specified level (the Daily OFO Level). Generally, during peak design day conditions, the Daily OFO Level will be equal to the currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity. Should expected conditions be different than peak design day conditions, the Daily OFO Level may be greater or less than the currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity specified in the Customer’s Application and Agreement. In order to determine compliance with the OFO, the Shipper may use gas quantities which are: 1) scheduled and delivered on that day to the Company in the same Pipeline Scheduling Point in which the Shipper’s facilities or other Delivery Point are located; 2) available pursuant to the Rider EBS-Option 1; or 3) additional quantities that may be made available to the Shipper by the Company at its discretion, including volumes delivered to the Company in a different Local Market Area than the Local Market Area in which the Shipper’s facilities or other Delivery Point are located.
(d) When a difference between the Daily OFO Level and actual daily OFO compliance quantities delivered to the Company exists, the following charges will be assessed to the Shipper:
(1) A rate equal to one and one-half (1 ½) times the highest of the midpoint prices reflected in Platts Gas Daily for the day of the OFO non-compliance and based on Pipeline Scheduling Point applicable indices as specified in Section 20.2, Platts “Gas Daily,” Daily Price Survey–Designation by Pipeline Scheduling Point, of this Part.
The charge will be multiplied by the therm difference, provided, however, that the charge will not be assessed if the difference results from the Shipper delivering more than the Daily OFO Level during an OFO that restricts under-deliveries, or from the Shipper delivering less than the Daily OFO Level during an OFO that restricts over-deliveries; and,
(2) The payment of all other charges incurred by the Company on the date of the OFO that results from the Shipper's failure to comply with the OFO, including a proportionate share of any pipeline penalties that are incurred by the Company.
(e) In the event midpoint prices referenced in Section 20.4(d) above are not published in Platts Gas Daily for the day of the OFO non-compliance, the highest price paid by the Company on that day shall be used as the index price.
(f) The Company shall update the applicable indices on 60 days’ notice to Shippers in the event of a change in applicable indices. Applicable indices are subject to change based upon changes in market circumstances.
20.5 Operational Matching Orders (OMOs)
(a) An OMO is a demand for specific actions on the part of Shippers. All Rate Schedule SDS and LDS Shippers with daily measurement equipped meters who have elected Telemetry, except as otherwise specified herein, are subject to the Company’s issuance of OMOs. This includes Shippers who currently have daily read analog telephone lines that are providing timely usage information and who have elected Telemetry and are waiting installation of the new cellular modem device.
(b) Shippers with daily measurement using an EFC who have elected Telemetry shall have a semi-annual option of choosing to be governed by OFOs or OMOs. Such option election shall be in writing and received by the Company no later than February 1st to be effective for the period of April 1st through October 31st, and no later than September 1st to be effective for the period of November 1st through March 31st. Once an eligible Shipper elects to be subject to an OFO, that election will remain in effect until the Shipper notifies the Company in writing of a different election. If no election is made, the default option shall be the OMO option. This includes Shippers who currently have daily read analog telephone lines that are providing timely usage information and who have elected Telemetry and are waiting for installation of the new cellular modem device.
(c) An OMO will be issued, to the extent possible, with a minimum of eight (8) hours’ notice to the affected parties. Notice shall be made by the medium most reasonably expected to reach the Shipper in a timely manner, including, but not limited to, e-mail, facsimile, or Nomination EBB. The notice will include the circumstance that warrants the issuance of the OMO and explain why the actions required are necessary.
(d) The Company shall have the authority to direct Shippers to adjust Shipper’s daily transportation volumes or daily scheduled deliveries (Daily OMO Level) in order that daily scheduled deliveries match Shipper’s transportation volumes. In order to comply with the OMO, the Shipper may use gas quantities which are: 1) scheduled and delivered on that day to the Company in the same Pipeline Scheduling Point in which the Shipper’s facilities or other Delivery Point are located; 2) available pursuant to Rider EBS-Option 1; or 3) additional quantities that may be made available to the Shipper by the Company at its discretion, including quantities delivered to a Local Market Area other than the Local Market area in which the Shipper’s facilities or other Delivery Point are located.
(e) No later than April 1st of each year a Shipper with a meter subject to an OMO shall select one of two options that the Company shall use to calculate the OMO Customer’s daily delivery requirement in the event of an equipment failure or network outage when such failure or outage prevents a Shipper from electronically retrieving the daily usage data by 1:00 PM Eastern Time for the Gas Day that ends at 10:00 AM Eastern Time on the same day. Such option selection shall be in writing and shall be effective for the following November 1st through October 31st period. The chosen option may only be changed for the subsequent November 1st through October 31st period by written notification received by the Company no later than the prior April 1st.
(1) Maximum Daily Quantity Option
The Shipper shall use the previously issued OFO/OMO NOTICE to identify the daily OFO percentage for the PSP in which the Shipper’s meter or other designated Delivery Point is located, and multiply the currently-effective MDQ for the Shipper’s meter by the OFO percentage to determine the confirmed delivery quantity required to comply with the OFO; or
(2) Transportation Volumes Option
The Shipper shall estimate actual Transportation Volumes for the following Gas Day and multiply such estimated usage by the OMO percentage specified in the previously issued OFO/OMO NOTICE for the PSP in which the Shipper’s meter or other Delivery Point is located to determine the confirmed delivery quantity required to comply with the OMO. The Company will multiply the actual transportation volumes by the applicable OMO percentage for that day to determine if the Customer or Shipper complied with the OMO.
If confirmed gas deliveries are out of compliance with the calculations specified in the Maximum Daily Quantity Option or the Transportation Volumes Option specified above, OMO penalties will be asessed based on the difference between the required confirmed delivery quantity and the actual confirmed Transportation Volumes for that day.
(f) When a difference exists between the Daily OMO Level and actual daily OMO compliance quantities delivered, charges will be assessed for non-compliance.
(C) (1) The non-compliance charges will be equal to one and one-half (1 ½) times the highest of the midpoint prices reflected in Platts Gas Daily for the day of the OMO non-compliance and based on Pipeline Scheduling Point applicable indices as specified in Section 20.2, Platts “Gas Daily”, Daily Price Survey – Designation by Pipeline Scheduling Point, of this Part.
(2) The charge will be multiplied by the therm difference, except that the charge will not be assessed if the difference results from the Shipper delivering more than the Daily OMO Level during an OMO that restricts under-deliveries, or from the Shipper delivering less than the Daily OMO Level during an OMO that restricts over-deliveries; and
(3) Customer will also be required to pay all other charges incurred by the Company on the date of the OMO that result from the Shipper's failure to comply with the OMO, including a proportionate share of any pipeline penalties that are incurred by the Company.

20.6 Limitations on Nominations
A Shipper shall not submit a daily gas transportation nomination in excess of one hundred percent (100%) of the Customer’s currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity except with the Company’s prior permission. The Company may reject a nomination to the extent it exceeds one hundred percent (100%) of a Customer’s currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity and confirm it at a level equal to the limit if the Shipper did not receive the Company’s prior permission.
20.7 Limitations on Excess Deliveries
The Company reserves the right to limit its receipt of deliveries which are in excess of a Customer’s transportation volumes on any given day (Excess Deliveries) when such Excess Deliveries may cause the Company to incur penalties for exceeding its allowed daily or total storage injection capacity of its supplying pipeline or to incur other costs to avoid or mitigate pipeline penalties. The level of the limitation shall be specified electronically by the Company to the Shipper. The Company shall bill a proportionate share of the penalties and other costs that were incurred to avoid or mitigate pipeline penalties to all Shippers who fail to comply with the Company’s limitation under this Section 20.7.
20.8 Takes in Excess of Deliveries (under-deliveries)
(a) If, in any billing cycle, the Customer’s actual transportation volumes, plus retainage on the distribution system, is greater than the sum of: (a) the quantity of gas delivered to the Company’s City Gate by the Shipper or other Receipt Point for the Shipper’s account during the billing cycle; plus (b) if the Shipper subscribes to EBS-Option 1, access to banked gas quantities as permitted under EBS-Option 1; plus (c) bank transfers performed for that cycle, then such use shall be considered imbalance gas sold by the Company to the Shipper.
(b) For Shippers electing Rider EBS-Option 1 or Rider EBS-Option 2, the price for such imbalance gas shall be sold by the Company at the higher of:
(1) a price equal to 120% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in the Platts Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint, plus the 100% load factor Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC FTS costs (including demand, commodity and retainage); or
(2) the highest commodity cost of purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the city gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty days before the beginning of the calendar month.
In addition, applicable taxes and Company transportation charges shall apply. Furthermore, if, in any month, Company incurs other charges, including gas costs, penalty charges or cash-outs caused by excess monthly under deliveries, the Shipper shall be charged its pro rata share of such charges.
During an SFO, the foregoing calculation shall be replaced by the table in Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, of this Part.
(c) The Shipper also shall be subject to the penalty set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, in the event that such purchases occur during the existence of an OFO or OMO condition.
(d) The purchase of imbalance gas pursuant to this section shall not relieve the Shipper of any applicable penalty resulting from the use of those quantities.
20.9 Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes (over-deliveries)
(a) If, in any billing cycle, the Shipper’s transportation volumes, plus retainage on the distribution system, is less than the sum of: (a) the quantity of gas delivered to the Company’s City Gate or other Receipt Point by the Shipper for the Shipper’s account during the billing cycle, minus (b) if the Shipper subscribes to Rider EBS-Option 1, increases in the Shipper’s positive bank as permitted under EBS-Option 1, plus (c) bank transfers performed for the billing cycle, then such deliveries shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company from the Shipper.
(b) For Shippers electing Rider EBS-Option 1 or Rider EBS-Option 2, the price of such imbalance gas shall be purchased by the Company at the lower of:
(1) a price equal to 80% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in the Platts Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint; or
(2) the lowest commodity cost of purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the City Gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty (30) days before the beginning of the calendar month.
In addition, if, in any month the Company incurs other charges, including gas costs, penalty charges, or cash-outs caused by excess monthly over-deliveries, the Shipper shall be charged its pro rata share of such charges.
During an SFO, the foregoing calculation shall be replaced by the table in Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, of this Part.
(c) The Shipper also shall be subject to the penalty set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, in the event that such sale occurs during the existence of an OFO or OMO condition.
(d) The purchase of imbalance gas pursuant to this section shall not relieve the Shipper of any applicable penalty resulting from the delivery of those quantities.
20.10 Limitation Where a Shipper Has a Positive Bank
The drawdown of a positive bank is not a firm transportation service, except as provided in Rider EBS-Option 1. Shippers electing Rider EBS-Option 1 shall have firm access to positive banks as specified in Rider EBS-Option 1. For Shippers electing Rider EBS-Option 2, the existence of a positive intra-cycle bank shall not prevent limitation of service to a Shipper pursuant to Section 19.7, Interruptions and Limitations of Gas Transportation Service, of this Part, and drawdowns of positive banks may be prohibited whenever, in the Company's judgment, such prohibition is necessary to ensure that sufficient gas supplies are available to meet the daily or seasonal requirements of the Company’s firm sales or transportation customers, including the balancing requirements of such customers.
20.11 Flow Order Management Service
(a) The Flow Order Management Service shall be available to Shippers using more than 540,000 thm per year served under Rate LDS. This service will allow the Rate LDS Shippers using more than 540,000 thm per year located in the same Pipeline Scheduling Point either to group together themselves, or to nominate an agent which shall group the Shippers together. Upon formation of such a group, each member’s compliance with a flow order shall be determined based upon the sum of the scheduled deliveries and the daily requirements of the group.
(b) During an SFO, OFO, or OMO, if the group, as a whole, has scheduled adequate deliveries to comply with the SFO, OFO, or OMO, then no penalties shall be assessed to any member of the group, regardless of whether that particular member complied with the SFO, OFO, or OMO.
(c) During an SFO, OFO, or OMO, if the group, as a whole, has not scheduled adequate deliveries to comply with the SFO, OFO, or OMO, then a penalty shall be calculated based upon the group’s overall non-compliance with the SFO, OFO, or OMO. The total penalty shall be divided by the number of members in the group, and that amount shall be billed to each member.
(d) The fee for Flow Order Management Service is set forth in the Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. A signed agreement must be completed prior to August 15th of the year in which the Flow Order Management Service is to commence. Shippers must subscribe to the Flow Order Management Service for an entire year, beginning in November.
