The Customer Charge will be determined based upon the Shipper’s actual transportation volumes, measured in therms (thm), for the twelve most recent billing cycle periods ending with the October billing cycle. If a Shipper does not have sufficient history to determine its Customer Charge based on twelve months’ volumes, the Customer Charge will be developed by annualizing the delivery history available. In the instance where a Shipper has no delivery history, the Company will request the Shipper to submit estimated annual gas transportation requirements, upon which to develop the Customer Charge. The Company in all cases retains the right to review and modify the Shipper’s estimate where necessary. A Shipper’s Customer Charge will remain constant annually, subject to change as of the January billing cycle of each year.
In all cases, the Company reserves the right to review the Customer Charge and, upon receipt of satisfactory proof, to adjust the Customer Charge to reflect changes in the Shipper’s gas transportation requirements.
The applicable Usage Charge for all transportation quantities shall be determined based upon the Customer Charge group in which the Customer is placed, as established annually above. State Tax Adjustment Surcharge (STAS) Service under Rate SDS is subject to a State Tax Adjustment Surcharge as set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates.
Distribution System Improvement Charge (DSIC) Service under Rate SDS is subject to a Distribution System Improvement Charge as set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently Effective Rates.
Elective Balancing Service Rider
Service under Rate SDS shall be subject to the provisions of Rider EBS, Elective Balancing Service, as set forth in this Part 3 of the Statement of Operating Conditions.
Terms of Payment and Late Payment Charge
Gas transported hereunder shall be billed in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth in the Customer's executed contract governing gas transportation service. Bills for transportation service will be rendered monthly and are due and payable upon presentation. All bills shall be paid on or before the final date of payment shown on the bill, which date shall not be less than fifteen (15) days after presentation (date of postmark).
If the Customer fails to pay the full amount of any bill a delayed payment charge of one and one- quarter percent (1 1/4%) per billing cycle shall accrue on the portion of the bill that is unpaid on the due date. Special Provisions Applicable to all SDS Customers 1. Customers desiring to transfer to or from this rate schedule will be allowed to do so only if: (1) the Company can obtain any increase or decrease in its transportation capacity or storage capacity, or any combination thereof, that is required to accommodate such transfer; or (2) the Company, in its judgment concludes that no increase or decrease is required. The Company shall establish the date any transfer is to be effective.
2. In the event Customer's gas transportation requirements, as determined annually under the Customer Charge provisions above, are in excess of 540,000 thm, the Customer shall be transferred to Rate LDS-Large Distribution Service, effective the immediately succeeding January billing cycle.
C. Rider EBS Elective Balancing Service Availability
Throughout the territory served under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
This Rider has been established to provide balancing service options for Rate LDS and Rate SDS Shippers taking service under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
As set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, in addition to the usage charges for service under Rate LDS or SDS, an amount may be added for each thm distributed by the Company for EBS service as provided below. Rider EBS contains two options for balancing service as described below.
Service Options: Option 1: Full Balancing Service Full Balancing Service provides the Shipper, as defined in Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, with the opportunity to: (1) maintain a bank from month to month on the Company’s system; (2) access banked gas on a firm basis pursuant to the Seasonal Flow Order, Operational Flow Order, and Matching Flow Order sections of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, including days in which an SFO, OFO, or OMO restricts under-deliveries, up to five percent (5%) of the Shipper’s currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity (“MDQ”), and, to the extent made available by the Company on a best efforts basis, additional interruptible access to the Shipper’s bank; and (3) to add to the bank on any day, including days in which an SFO, OFO, or OMO restricts over-deliveries. Deliveries to the Company on days in which an SFO, OFO, or OMO restricts over-deliveries shall not exceed one hundred two and one-half percent (102.5%) of the maximum prescribed SFO, OFO, or OMO Level unless authorized by the Company. Option 1: Bank Tolerance The cumulative balance of excess deliveries (“positive bank”), at the end of any billing month, shall not exceed the following specified Bank Tolerance Percentages:
1. For any Shipper with annual consumption greater than 540,000 thm - 5% of the Shipper’s then-current annual quantities.
2. For any Shipper with annual consumption less than or equal to 540,000 thm – 10% of the Shipper’s then-current annual quantities as specified for the billing months of November through September, and 5% of the Shipper’s then-current annual quantity for the October billing month.
Option 1: Rates
The rates for EBS-Option 1 will be calculated on an annual basis by the Company. The Company shall calculate the rates after Shippers have elected their service options and after the Company has secured the assets that are required to provide the service. These rates shall take effect on April 1 of each year. The rates are set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. Option 1: Electing Service Option 1 is the default service option under Rider EBS. Any Rate LDS or Rate SDS Shipper who has not elected to take service under one of the other options shall automatically take service under Option 1. A Shipper may elect to change its service option no more than one time per year. An estimate of the rates shall be posted on the Company’s EBB on August 1 of each year. All requests to change the service option must be submitted to the Company in writing (e.g., fax, e-mail, electronic bulletin board) no later than the fifteenth of August prior to the April in which the elected option becomes effective. The EBS-Option 1 final rate will be posted on the Company’s EBB on September 1. If the September 1 final rate exceeds the August 1 estimated rate by more than 20%, Shippers who have elected EBS-Option 1 may change their election by submitting a change to the Company in writing (e.g., fax, e-mail, EBB) no later than the fifteenth of September. The elected option shall remain in effect for the one-year period commencing April 1 of the following calendar year. A Shipper shall elect its service option at the time it executes its Application and Agreement; however, if the new Shipper executes its Application and Agreement after August 15, the Company is under no obligation to provide service to the Shipper under Option 1 until April of the next following year if the Company does not have adequate storage and capacity assets to provide the service. If the Company cannot serve the new Shipper under Option 1 until April of the next following year, the Company will either: (a) serve the Shipper under Option 2 during the interim; or (b) elect to limit/reduce the Elective Balancing Services under Option 1 for the new Shipper.
The Company’s obligation to provide service under Option 1 is conditioned upon its ability to secure the assets necessary to provide the service. If sufficient assets are not available to provide Option 1 service, Shippers will default to Option 2.
Option 1: Character of Service Normal Operations In any billing month under Normal Operations (defined as operations during times when neither an SFO, OFO, nor an OMO is in effect), if the Shipper’s transportation volumes plus retainage on the distribution system exceed the sum of: (a) the quantity of gas delivered to the Company’s City Gate or other Receipt Point for the Shipper’s account during the billing month, plus (b) the Shipper’s positive bank at the beginning of the month, such use shall be considered imbalance gas sold by the Company to the Shipper under the provisions of the Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. If in any billing month under Normal Operations, the Shipper’s transportation volumes plus retainage on the distribution system are less than the quantity of gas delivered into the Company's system on its behalf, the Shipper may use such excess delivered gas to meet requirements in any succeeding billing month, subject to the Company's rights to limit service as provided in Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. Provided, however, that the cumulative balance of excess deliveries ("positive bank") at the end of any billing month shall not exceed the Bank Tolerance Percentage. Any positive bank in excess of this tolerance level shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company from the Shipper under the provisions of the Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. During SFOs/OFOs/OMOs
During periods when there is an SFO, OFO, or OMO that restricts under-deliveries, EBS Option 1 Shippers will have firm daily access to banks equal to five percent (5%) of the Shipper’s currently effective Maximum Daily Quantity (“MDQ”). Additional interruptible access to bank capacity will be available on a best-efforts basis. Should a Shipper on any SFO, OFO, or OMO day under-deliver gas supplies to the Company by a quantity greater than 5% of the Shipper’s currently effective MDQ and any interruptible access to the bank permitted through the SFO, OFO, or OMO notice, such quantities shall be charged to the Shipper in accordance with Section 20.5, Seasonal Flow Orders, Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, and Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, as is appropriate to the circumstance. If on any day, the Shipper’s bank is not adequate to support any part or all of the bank access made available by the Company and the resulting bank availability combined with other confirmed deliveries by the Shipper is less than the daily delivery requirement under the SFO, OFO, or OMO, the Shipper will be charged for any delivery deficiency in accordance with Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, and Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. At the end of any month in which there has been an SFO, OFO, or OMO that restricts under-deliveries, authorized bank withdrawals used to help meet the daily delivery requirements of an OFO or OMO will be deemed to be the first gas withdrawn from the bank, followed by authorized bank withdrawals used to help meet the daily delivery requirements of an SFO during the month. Any remaining available bank quantities will be applied to days of Normal Operations. Authorized bank withdrawals herein are considered to be the firm access provided under EBS Option 1 plus any interruptible access provided by the Company subject to the Shipper(s) having sufficient quantities in its (their) bank to support the access permitted by the Company.
During periods when there is an SFO, OFO, or OMO restriction of over-deliveries, Shippers will be entitled to deliver to the Company up to one hundred two and one-half percent (102.5%) of the Company's maximum prescribed daily SFO, OFO, or OMO quantity. However, should daily deliveries exceed one hundred two and one-half percent (102.5%) of the Shipper’s maximum daily prescribed SFO, OFO, or OMO quantity, or if the cumulative excess deliveries exceed the bank tolerances described above, those excess daily deliveries shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company pursuant to Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, or Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating conditions and the Shipper shall be charged in accordance with the Seasonal Flow Order, Operational Flow Order, or Operational Matching Order provisions contained in that part.
Option 1: Imbalance Trading Services
A) Bank Balance Transfers
During Normal Operations, subject to Section 19.7, Interruptions and Limitations of Gas Transportation Service, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, Shippers who subscribe to Rider EBS-Option 1 may transfer a bank balance that existed at the beginning of the month to another Shipper that has also subscribed to Rider EBS-Option 1 and that also schedules deliveries to the Company's city-gates within the same Pipeline Scheduling Point. No pre-arranged contract is required. The Shipper must submit all requests for Bank Balance Transfers to the Company in writing (e.g., fax, e-mail, electronic bulletin board) no later than the third business day following the last business day of the calendar month in which the trade is to apply. A fee for each balance transfer shall be charged to the Shipper transferring the bank balance. The fee is set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. EBS-Option 1 Shippers who successfully transfer bank balances to eliminate an imbalance will not be subject to Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, or Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
During any month in which an SFO, OFO, or OMO was in effect, Shippers who subscribe to Rider EBS-Option 1 may transfer a bank balance that existed at the beginning of the month to another Shipper who is located in the same Pipeline Scheduling Point that has also subscribed to Rider EBS-Option 1 and that schedules deliveries to the Company's city-gates on the same transmission company. Provided, however, that bank balance transfers will apply to the SFO, OFO, or OMO period only up to the level of daily access to banked quantities authorized by the OFO, OMO, or SFO. No pre-arranged contract is required. The Shipper must submit all requests for Bank Balance Transfers to the Company in writing (e.g., fax, e-mail, electronic bulletin board) no later than the first business day following the last business day of the calendar month in which the trade is to apply. A fee per transfer, for transfers within a Pipeline Scheduling Point, shall be charged to the Shipper transferring the bank balance. The fee is set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. EBS-Option 1 Shippers who successfully transfer bank balances to eliminate an imbalance will not be subject to Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, and Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
The imbalance trading services set forth in this Rider do not relieve Shippers of their obligation to deliver gas to the Company in the Pipeline Scheduling Point in which their facilities or other designated Delivery Points(s) are located.
(b) Gas Transfer Service
Availability
During Normal Operations or periods during which an SFO, OFO, or OMO is in effect, subject to Section 19.7, Interruptions and Limitations of Gas Transportation Service, of this Statement of Operating Conditions, this optional service is available to Shippers who subscribe to Rider EBS-Option 1. This service provides for the transfer of gas quantities from one Shipper (“Transferor”) to another Shipper (“Transferee”).
Character of Service
(a) Each transfer must occur such that gas is transferred from the Transferor to the Transferee on the same Gas Day. Transferor must request the transfer at the end of the current month, as described in subparagraph (e) below.
(b) Transfers may only occur between a Transferor and a Transferee located within the same Local Market Area with confirmed deliveries on the same transmission pipeline.
(c) Quantities eligible for transfer shall not exceed the Transferor’s confirmed deliveries for the day of transfer. A transfer request may not be accepted by the Company if such transfer would cause the Transferor to incur imbalance charges.
(d) Shippers must rely on Shipper transportation volumes posted daily on the Company’s website. The Company shall post Shipper transportation volumes on its Internet-based website as soon as practicable after the end of each Gas Day throughout the billing cycle. All Shipper transportation volumes will be posted on a best-efforts basis by 5:00 p.m., Eastern time, on the second business day following the end of the previous calendar month.
(e) All gas transfer requests must be accurately completed and executed by both the Transferor and the Transferee and submitted to the Company on the Company’s standard Gas Transfer Request Form by 5:00 p.m., Eastern time, on the third business day following the end of the previous calendar month.
(f) The Company is not involved in any arrangement or agreement for compensation for the value of the gas being transferred, or for any other fees between the Transferor and Transferee. The Company’s role in administering this rate schedule is limited to transferring the approved gas quantities from the Transferor’s to the Transferee’s account with the Company.
Rate
The Company will charge the Transferor a fee for each transaction. The fee is set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates.
Option 1: Termination of Service
Shippers may terminate service under Option 1 only by electing another option in accordance with the provisions set forth in this Rider or by terminating transportation service. A Shipper who is terminating transportation service may be charged a termination fee if the Shipper fails to provide termination notice prior to the fifteenth of September prior to the April in which the service is to be terminated. Such termination fee shall be based upon the cost of the assets secured by the Company to provide service to the Shipper. Upon termination of service under Option 1, the Company will make every effort to deliver to or for the Shipper the Shipper’s banked gas during the next month’s billing cycle following the date of termination. However, should Shipper fail to take delivery of or otherwise transport its entire bank of gas within the next month, Company may, at its option, retain and purchase the undelivered bank of gas at a rate determined pursuant to Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. In addition, if the Shipper owes the Company any outstanding charges, the Company may retain as an offset to such outstanding charges, banked gas that would otherwise be delivered to Shipper upon termination of transportation service. The value assigned to such retained bank of gas which is purchased or retained will be a rate determined pursuant to Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions for the month in which the Shipper failed to take delivery of the gas.
Option 2: Monthly Cash Out (Intra-Month Balancing Service)
Intra-Month Balancing Service provides Shippers with: (1) the opportunity to maintain a bank from day to day within a month on the Company’s system; (2) limited or no use of the bank during issuance of an SFO, OFO, or OMO pursuant to Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, and Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions, and (3) a monthly cash-out of any bank of gas existing at the end of the month. Option 2: Rates
Rates for Intra-Month Balancing Service are set forth in the Part 1, Statement of Currently- Effective Rates.
Option 2: Electing Service Option 2 must be elected by the Shipper in writing (e.g., fax, e-mail, electronic bulletin board). A Shipper may elect to change its service option no more than one time per year. All requests to change the service option must be submitted to the Company in writing (e.g. fax, e-mail, electronic bulletin board) no later than the fifteenth of August prior to the April in which the elected option becomes effective. The elected option shall remain in effect from April 1 through March 31 of the following calendar year.
Option 2: Character of Service
Normal Operations In any billing month under Normal Operations, if the Shipper transports more gas than the quantity of gas, after adjustments for retainage, delivered to the Company's City Gate or other Receipt Point by the Shipper for the Shipper's account during the billing month, such use shall be considered imbalance gas sold by the Company to the Shipper under the provisions of Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
If in any billing month, under normal operations, the Shipper transports less gas than the quantity of gas delivered to the Company's City Gate or other Receipt Point by the Shipper, such use shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company from the Shipper under the provisions of Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
During SFO
If the Shipper under-delivers during an SFO that restricts under-deliveries, the Shipper will be charged for under-deliveries in accordance with Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. If the Shipper over-delivers during an SFO that restricts over-deliveries, the over-deliveries shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company from the Shipper pursuant to Section 20.3, Seasonal Flow Orders, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. The Shipper shall have access to any positive intra-month bank only to the extent specified by the Company in an SFO.
During OFO/OMO
If the Shipper under-delivers during an OFO or OMO that restricts under-deliveries, the Shipper will be charged for under-deliveries in accordance with Section 20.8, Takes in Excess of Deliveries, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions and either Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, or Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, of that Part. If the Shipper over-delivers during an OFO or OMO that restricts over-deliveries, the over-deliveries shall be considered imbalance gas purchased by the Company from the Shipper pursuant to Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions and the Shipper shall be charged in accordance with either Section 20.4, Operational Flow Orders, or Section 20.5, Operational Matching Orders, of that part. On a best efforts basis, the Company may offer the Shipper daily access to any positive intra-month bank only to the extent specified by the Company in an OFO or OMO. Such best-efforts access shall not be subject to charges under either the OFO or OMO sections of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions nor shall it alter the Shipper’s obligation to be in balance at the end of the month in accordance with the provisions of EBS-Option 2.
Option 2: Termination of Service
Shippers may terminate service under Option 2 only by electing another option as described in this Rider or by terminating gas transportation service. Upon termination of service under Option 2, the Company will calculate imbalance gas sold or purchased by the Company from the Shipper as described in the “Normal Operations” section above. However, if the Shipper owes the Company any outstanding charges, the Company may retain as an offset to such outstanding charges, banked gas or over-deliveries that would otherwise be delivered to the Shipper upon termination of service. The value assigned to such retained bank of gas or over-deliveries which are purchased will be ninety percent (90%) of the index rate determined pursuant to Section 20.9, Deliveries in Excess of Transportation Volumes, of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions. 58 28513800v1
